<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-048-091 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 319 723</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Sources  Oct 1991 v2 n10 p75(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microtek unveils monitors. (Microtek Lab Inc.'s MCD-1403,MCD-1414) (Forum)(Brief Article) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Antonoff, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microtek Lab Inc. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   Microtek Lab MCD-1403 (Monitor, color) (Product introduction)Microtek Lab MCD-1404 (Monitor, color) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     MonitorsColorProduct Introduction.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Microtek Lab (Torrance, CA, 800-654-4160, 213-321-2121), known for itsscanner products, has entered the monitor business with the introduction oftwo 14-inch color displays.andM;The MCD-1403 monitor ($1,099 list) incorporates a Sony Triniton picture tubewith a .25mm dot pitch.andP;  It offers a resolution of 1,280 by 1,024 pixels in anon-interlaced display.andM;The MCD-1404 ($999 list) uses a Hitachi tube, and offers a .28mm dot pitchand a 1,280 by 1,024 non-interlaced display.andP;  Both Microtek monitors arecompatible with VGA and XGA display adapters.andP;  A $15 adapter is available toconnect either one to a Macintosh II computer.andM;Preprogrammed, microprocessor-based controls let the monitors automaticallyadjust to standard display modes.andP;  You can also store up to nine userprogrammed display settings and restore them by pressing a button.andP;  Bothmonitors will be available by mail, but at press time prcies were not yetavailable.andM;Also, at the time of this writing, Microtek planned to extend the MCD line inlate summer with the introduction of two additional monitors, a 15-inchflat-screen color unit and a 17-inch color one.andO;</TEXT></DOC>